reviewText:
The original Resident Evil was released for PlayStation back in 1996 and it was a sucess, in 2002 Capcom remade the game for Nintendo Gamecube, they had improved the graphics, gameplay and added new stuff, items and puzzles, the new game, known as Resident Evil REmake then took the original's game place in the story's timeline.
This one is the HD Remaster of the 2002 Gamecube remake, I'll point out a few pros and cons of this edition:

Pros:

â€¢ Improved graphics, textures, creatures and character models;
â€¢ New grapphics settings that were not possible by the time of the original release;
â€¢ Support for 16:9 screens up to 4k (an edit on the game .ini file is required for resolutions bigger than 1080p);
â€¢ Support for 4:3 screens.
â€¢ Support for fixed 30, fixed 60 and variable framerates, good for all sorts of computers;
â€¢ Full Xbox 360 controller support, keyboard and mouse and as well two controll modes, one being the classic, that is similar to the Gamecube edition and the alternate, which is similar to the modern titles from the Resident Evil series;
â€¢ Good reply value, you can play several times to earn the different in-game unlockables (such as costumes and weapons) as well earn achievements.
â€¢ Several game modes to make the game harder and more interesting once you finish it once, you can also make it even easier should you prefer.

Cons:

â€¢ Huge size, almost 20gb for a game that was originally played on two 1.5gb mini-discs;
â€¢ Doesn't have have native support for resolutions that are not 4:3 or 16:9, also some of the 16:9 resolutions are not avaliable at the game options and require to be manually changed at the .ini file;
â€¢ Background graphics have not received the same treatment as the characters and creatures, they look a bit blurry on higher resolutions, they're better than the Gamecube version though;
â€¢ Cutscenes were not remade at all, they look super blurry because they were stretched from 460p used by Gamecube;
â€¢ Not the best game to be played with keyboard and mouse, while it's still playable, a controller is highly recommended.


My conclusion:
The game is great, it has a great story, it can be hard for those who prefer and easy for those who don't.
You can play this for many hours to unlock everything and all achievements, so lots of fun for quite some time.
Minor graphics problems that won't ruin the game at all.
It's worth the 20 bucks, the game is great and brings back memories, also buying it will be enough to tell Capcom that we have interest in seeying the other RE games to be remade and brought to PC too.

Note: some people were not able to play the game due to slowdowns, even people with PCs far better than my own, some complained about audio issues or crashes, I got the game on pre-sale and played for about 9 hours and finished the game with Jill without a single audio, graphic and crash issue, therefore the game is working a 100% for me.

Update: fixed a few typing mistakes, english is not my main language and made a few mistakes that needed to be fixed.

14 years have passed since I played Resident Evil for the first time on my Playstation, and it still feels scary, lonely and freaking awesome. Even more at 1080p, 60fps and with a whole new physics made exclusively for Jill's boobs! Jiggle jiggle!

Pros;
Great atmosphere;
Nostalgia all over the place;
60fps and 1080p;
It is hard as it should be, without that Hollywood-ish action nonsense.

Cons;
Textures can feel a little blurry from time to time;
Voice acting still kind of sucks.

Got bitten by a giant snake and died trying to find the Serum because I forgot where the room was. 10/9.1 would get bitten again!

This game is still as good as it was when it was first for PS1 (I never played the gamecube/wii version) with updated graphics from the GC remake. You can play with a new modern controls or the tank controls and choose what graphics, resolution and more things in the settings (althoug there is few options).

List of positive/negative things that I've noted at my first playthrough

Positive  The game still feels like it's first release, with some minor tweaks/changes (like I've said, I've never played the GC/WII copy);
Lets you choose what kind of FPS and if you want to play with original resolution or by 16:9;
The game have some replayability (if you want to do the archivements or find about another endings or unlock all costumes/extra weapons) so you can wait some time and you will feel that your money is worth paying full price;
Like I've said you get archivements, a leadboard (evem though I think it's already hacked because i've saw some people finish the game less than 10 min, until I see an video of that, I will not belive on that), and full support to the Xbox 360 gamepad (I do own one and played with him, felt great).

Neutral
The Crimson Head, Fuel Canister and Lighter (for Jill only, as Chris starts with the Lighter) are a good new thing, it makes you think even more if you should take that items with you (if you shot and kill the zombie) to evade the possibility of they reviving as Crimson Head's zombies, or you just don't have the space so you shouldn't kill and just evade zombies (but still it takes up to two inventory slots and if one inventory slot filled makes you even consider what should you take or not with you, think about two as Jill with lower Heath and Damage). I do think that this actually is a positive thing (but still I do not like them hehe) but it was not released when the first Resident Evil came out so some people may dislike and even rage more as the game is not hard enough as it is.

Negative
There are some issues in some areas of the game (mainly FPS drops). I did get rarely for the first part of the game, but in some parts or areas, my fps drops would go down for 25 FPS per second. It's probably not well optimised for some parts of the game or it's my CPU problem (but I don't belive in the latter as my CPU can handle more demaning games just fine, even being an Pentium G-3258 3,2 GHz [I didn't overclocked yet but this CPU is a Beast at 4-4,5 GHz, but still it can't compare to an i7] it should run well) I hope that they will bring some updates as it seems that some people are getting the same problem with better CPU's than mine. Also people complain about their mobile GPU's not working well, CAPCOM warned about that not being supported on the Requirements List of the game page but still they should look for some fix or update as many people also game on laptops (this last sentence is an opinion as not all laptop users had that problem but some complained about that in the forums);
The lack of an type of Mercenarys or like Sega Saturn's release: Battle Game minigame after your first playthrough. It would be even better as you could even take more hours to the game;
Some desynchronization in the cutscenes. It was not all the time, but from some of them have that problem;
Some areas are low rendered. The detail in the overall it's great, but some wall's/textures/cutscenes were poorly upgraded to 1080p.


My final rating at this game : 8,0/10.

Why? Because it mantains the core of the game, with only few tweaks/changes/additions for the better on my perspective, but they should had more carefull updating the game to the modern day as they have some desynchronization and low rendered textures in some parts of the game.
